comments: Many of these questions are notapplicable to this course, since the course is a doctoral lab that does not have regular instruction or readings. Rather, we use it as a forum to present and discuss ongoing work and projects of people within the social ecology doctoral group, and to discuss other key skills or topics of interest to the group, like preparation for qualifying exams or applying for academic jobs. This course is extremely valuable for me - I've learned a lot from my peers and greatly benefit from their feedback.

This is peculiar course, hence many of the questions above do not apply. I enjoy the lab a lot: although not in every session, as a whole it is impressively useful. It is the main source of guidance I have for my phd program!

narratives.question_text: The things about this course most in need of improvement are:
comments: Students are free to share and discuss about their project, and contribute to each other ideas. However, when we do so informally, outside class, we are even better. Why can't we think together in a formal setting? Do we feel on a stage all the time? Have we adjusted to think according to the context? Although this lab is the best place I found to share ideas in my all program, I still think there is something that can still be improved.

narratives.question_text: What was the availability and quality of help you received of the instructor and TA?
comments: Professor Dove comments are inspiring even when on somebody else's work.

narratives.question_text: Discuss if you wish how this course fits into your overall program.
comments: This course is very beneficial in my overall program - it helps me learn from other social ecology doctoral students, especially those further along in the program, about their research and helps me think through my own research.

narratives.question_text: Why did you take this course?
comments: This is a reliably useful course that I will continue to take semesterly while I am in residence in New Haven.
